[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> w,h=2400,1800
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> # Let's compute the sky color as function of direction
[?2004l[?2004h> # The sky seems to have a gradient that depends on zenith angle
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> # For each pixel, compute the direction vector
[?2004l[?2004h> # Camera is at (0, camera_height, 0) looking along -z? Or looking down?
[?2004l[?2004h> # Actually, in a typical ray tracer, the camera looks along some direction
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> # Let's check if the sky color depends on the ray direction
[?2004l[?2004h> # For sky pixel (x,y), compute direction:
[?2004l[?2004h> # dx = (x - w/2) / (w/2)
[?2004l[?2004h> # dy = -(y - h/2) / (h/2)  
[?2004l[?2004h> # dz = -1 (looking into screen)
[?2004l[?2004h> # Normalize
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> # Then check the relationship with the zenith angle (angle from up vector)
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> print("Checking sky color vs zenith angle:")
[?2004l[?2004h> for y in range(0, 901, 100):
[?2004l[?2004h>     for x in [0, 600, 1200, 1800, 2399]:
